"Hikami M., Ushie H., Irie T., Fujita K., Kuroyanagi A., Sakai K., Nojiri Y., Suzuki A., Kawahata H.","Contrasting calcification responses to ocean acidification between two reef foraminifers harboring different algal symbionts",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","19", L19601,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL048501,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053969714&partnerID=40&md5=f04fc978865c210faefc13e958c31d2b","Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan; Department of Biology, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305-5020, United States; Department of Physics and Earth Sciences, University of the Ryukyus, 1 Senbaru, Nishihara, Okinawa 903-0213, Japan; Sesoko Station, Tropical Biosphere Research Center, University of the Ryukyus, Motobu, Okinawa 905-0227, Japan; Center for Global Environmental Research, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan; Geological Survey of Japan, National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology, 1-1-1 Higashi, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8567, Japan","Hikami, M., Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan; Ushie, H., Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan; Irie, T., Department of Biology, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305-5020, United States; Fujita, K., Department of Physics and Earth Sciences, University of the Ryukyus, 1 Senbaru, Nishihara, Okinawa 903-0213, Japan; Kuroyanagi, A., Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan; Sakai, K., Sesoko Station, Tropical Biosphere Research Center, University of the Ryukyus, Motobu, Okinawa 905-0227, Japan; Nojiri, Y., Center for Global Environmental Research, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan; Suzuki, A., Geological Survey of Japan, National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology, 1-1-1 Higashi, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8567, Japan; Kawahata, H., Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan","Ocean acidification, which like global warming is an outcome of anthropogenic CO<inf>2</inf> emissions, severely impacts marine calcifying organisms, especially those living in coral reef ecosystems. However, knowledge about the responses of reef calcifiers to ocean acidification is quite limited, although coral responses are known to be generally negative. In a culture experiment with two algal symbiont-bearing, reef-dwelling foraminifers, Amphisorus kudakajimensis and Calcarina gaudichaudii, in seawater under five different pCO<inf>2</inf> conditions, 245, 375, 588, 763 and 907 μatm, maintained with a precise pCO<inf>2</inf>-controlling technique, net calcification of A. kudakajimensis was reduced under higher pCO<inf>2</inf>, whereas calcification of C. gaudichaudii generally increased with increased pCO<inf>2</inf>. In another culture experiment conducted in seawater in which bicarbonate ion concentrations were varied under a constant carbonate ion concentration, calcification was not significantly different between treatments in Amphisorus hemprichii, a species closely related to A. kudakajimensis, or in C. gaudichaudii. From these results, we concluded that carbonate ion and CO <inf>2</inf> were the carbonate species that most affected growth of Amphisorus and Calcarina, respectively. The opposite responses of these two foraminifer genera probably reflect different sensitivities to these carbonate species, which may be due to their different symbiotic algae. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Acidification; Biomineralization; Bone; Carbon dioxide; Carbonation; Experiments; Global warming; Ions; Reefs; Seawater; Carbonate ions; Carbonate species; Coral reef ecosystems; Foraminifers; Ion concentrations; Calcification (biochemistry); acidification; anthropogenic effect; atmospheric pollution; bearing capacity; calcification; carbon dioxide; coral reef; environmental degradation; foraminifera; global warming; growth rate; harbor; seawater; symbiont; algae; Amphisorus; Amphisorus hemprichii; Anthozoa; Calcarina; Calcarina gaudichaudii; Foraminifera",,,,,,"Badger, M.R., Andrews, T.J., Whitney, S.M., Ludwig, M., Yellowlees, D.C., Leggat, W., Price, G.D., The diversity and coevolution of Rubisco, plastids, pyrenoids, and chloroplast-based CO<inf>2</inf>-concentrating mechanisms in algae (1998) Canadian Journal of Botany, 76 (6), pp. 1052-1071; Bijma, J., Spero, H., Lea, D., Reassessing foraminiferal stable isotope geochemistry: Impact of the oceanic carbonate system (experimental results) (1999) Use of Proxies in Paleoceanography: Examples from the South Atlantic, pp. 489-512. , edited by G. Fischer and G. Wefer Springer, Berlin; Dickson, A.G., Millero, F.J., A comparison of the equilibrium constants for the dissociation of carbonic acid in seawater media (1987) Deep Sea Res., 34, pp. 1733-1743. , doi:10.1016/0198-0149(87)90021-5; Doney, S.C., Fabry, V.J., Feely, R.A., Kleypas, J.A., Ocean acidification: The other CO<inf>2</inf> problem (2009) Annu. Rev. Mar. Sci., 1, pp. 169-192. , doi:10.1146/annurev.marine.010908.163834; Engel, A., Schulz, K.G., Riebesell, U., Bellerby, R., Delille, B., Schartau, M., Effects of CO<inf>2</inf> on particle size distribution and phytoplankton abundance during a mesocosm bloom experiment (PeECE II) (2008) Biogeosciences, 5 (2), pp. 509-521; Fabry, V.J., Ocean science: Marine calcifiers in a high-CO<inf>2</inf> ocean (2008) Science, 320 (5879), pp. 1020-1022. , DOI 10.1126/science.1157130; Fujita, K., Fujimura, H., Organic and inorganic carbon production by algal symbiont-bearing foraminifera on northwest Pacific coral-reef flats (2008) Journal of Foraminiferal Research, 38 (2), pp. 117-126. , DOI 